sections.text:
Atmospheric qCO2 was a major driver of Phanerozoic climate (Royer et al. 2004). Climate models indicate very high qCO2 values (8–20 PAL (Pre-Industrial Atmospheric Level)) in the Early Palaeozoic before a large drop in the Devonian–Carboniferous in response to weathering induced by large vascular plants on continents (e.g. Berner 1991, 1994, 2006a, b; Berner and Kothavala 2001;
Fig. 1). Such high values, indicative of a greenhouse world, have to be reconciled with at least temporary falls to qCO2 <8 PAL required for Late Ordovician glaciation(s) to occur. Among the physical parameters used in model simulations to reduce qCO2 are continental silicate weathering, degassing fluxes from volcanism and orogenesis, and evolving palaeogeography with associated changes in sea level and ocean circulation (e.g. Berner models, Herrmann et al. 2004a; Godd eris et al. 2014; Nardin et al. 2011; Pohl et al. 2014). A long-term cooling trend from the Cambrian to modern equatorial temperatures for Middle–Late Ordovician seawater is predicted from d18O stable isotopes (Trotter et al. 2008). Among few values reconstructed from d13C for atmospheric qCO2, ~16 PAL was reported from the Late Ordovician (Yapp and Poths 1992).
Globally, high sea levels in the Ordovician, which submerged continental margins in mid-low latitudes under vast areas of epeiric seas, reached a Palaeozoic maximum in the Late Ordovician (early Katian ~225 m above present day; Haq and Schutter 2008; Fig. 2A–C). With reduced land surface areas, low albedo would feed back to high temperatures. The Hirnantian climax of Late Ordovician glaciation(s) was accompanied by a sharp sea-level fall of 50–100 m (Brenchley 2004). Herrmann et al.’s (2004b) model simulations indicate that for ice sheets to form and glaciation to occur, even with reduced qCO2 to PAL 8, both a fall in sea level and reduction in poleward heat transport through ocean circulation would be necessary. Early Silurian post-glacial transgression reflooded the continental shelves as another long-term deepening trend culminated in a mid-Silurian high before steady decline through into the Early Devonian (Emsian; Haq and Schutter 2008;
Fig. 2D–F).
